I had some time to spare, so I made a proof of concept. It&#39;s in Kotlin because that&#39;s what I had available, but it should be easy to convert to Java:

```kotlin
fun &lt;V&gt; getAllThreadLocalValues(threadLocal: ThreadLocal&lt;V&gt;): Map&lt;Thread, V&gt; {
    val threadLocalsField = Thread::class.java.getDeclaredField(&quot;threadLocals&quot;)
        .apply { trySetAccessible() }
    val getEntryMethod = Class.forName(&quot;java.lang.ThreadLocal\$ThreadLocalMap&quot;)
        .getDeclaredMethod(&quot;getEntry&quot;, ThreadLocal::class.java)
        .apply { trySetAccessible() }
    val entryValueField = Class.forName(&quot;java.lang.ThreadLocal\$ThreadLocalMap\$Entry&quot;)
        .getDeclaredField(&quot;value&quot;)
        .apply { trySetAccessible() }

    return Thread.getAllStackTraces().mapValues { (thread, _) -&gt;
        val map = threadLocalsField.get(thread) ?: return@mapValues null
        val entry = getEntryMethod.invoke(map, threadLocal) ?: return@mapValues null
        val value = entryValueField.get(entry) ?: return@mapValues null
        value as V
    }.filterValues { it != null } as Map&lt;Thread, V&gt;
}
```

This code returns a map of `Thread` to the value of the passed `ThreadLocal`, if any. Threads without a value aren&#39;t included in the map.

Note that you&#39;ll need to pass `--add-opens=java.base/java.lang=ALL-UNNAMED` to allow the reflection.

